						<summary>

						<p>On a Slab set up in front of the Śilaiyammaṉ temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Rājakēsarivarman: Year 24: 894 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This inscription may be assigned to c. 9th Century on grounds of palaeography.</p>						

						<p>It records a grant of land (names specified) alongwith income from taxes as <hi rend="italic">ērippaṭṭi</hi> for the maintenance of a lake at Neṟkuṉṟam on the eastern direction of Śiṅgapura-nāḍu by Nambiyamallaṉār, son of Nṛipatuṅgamaṅgalappēraraiyaṉ. One of the taxes referred to here is termed <hi rend="italic">āṉavāy-daṇḍam.</hi> The name Nṛipatuṅgamaṅgalappēraraiyaṉ seems to suggest that he should have been named after the Pallava king Nṛipatuṅgavarman.</p>						

						<p>The high regnal year of the king and the palaeography of the record helps us to identify this Rajakēsarivarman with Chōḷa Āditya I.</p>						

						<p>(Published in <hi rend="italic">S.I.I.</hi> Vol. III, No. 93; and Ibid., Vol. XIII, No. 308). </p>						

						</summary>
